Timing Hero is a reaction action game. You'll be spamming one attack and dodging multiple as enemies with different speeds and attack patterns block the hero's path. Losing means starting over from the beginning of a stage. However, defeating monsters award points, used to upgrade character stats by a noticeable amount, so repeat battles are less tedious. I also found the pixelated aesthetics and action-packed music appealing. In the end, I had fun with the simple and fast-paced experience. 5/5.

I've played this game on and off. There's a BIG secret to getting good fast. There's a rather simple way to NOT watch the AD for free Gems. I'm talking a TON of Ads bypassed while gaining gems every second. So when you click Free Gems, on the top right is an X button for a split second before the AD. Click Free Gems/Watch Ad whatever it is. Once you click it, tap the top right of the screen repeatedly where the X will be. It'll close out and give you the gems without watching an AD.

This game gets a lot of things right. 1. Controls are simple and intuitive. 
Not really much to learn here except theres back, up, down and an attack 
button. 2. Customizability. Upgrade your heroes as you see fit. Novice with 
consistent damage, an archer with sufficient dodge and recovery, a glass 
cannon mage or a tanky warrior. Doesnt limit you to how you want to play 
it. You can be patient and build up your rage for your counterattack or be 
aggressive and increase your damage output. 3. High risk high reward 
gameplay. The title says it all and it delivers. Get the timing right for 
each enemy and youre rewarded handsomely. Strike as soon as the monster 
pops up and you get a critical hit guaranteed or dodge just before the 
strike and your rage meter builds up faster for a counter attack. 4. 
Grinding isnt boring since every enemy although they may have the same 
attacks dont use the same pattern each time so you need to pay attention, 
and the upgrades are significant enough to make grinding worthwhile. 5. 
Your choices matter. Maybe not in some grandplot, but whether you do decide 
to attack or not affects your fight. You cant just mash buttons and hope 
for the best. You have to watch your opponent and time every attack or you 
die. Diagonal down, diagonal up, two lanes forward, one lane forward, and 
successive strikes. These are the attacks enemies would make. But their 
positions on the screen vary. If you dont pay attention, theyll whittle you 
down fast. My gripes on the game is few and largely insignificant. The 
music is bland. 1st gen pokemon did a great job and so did other games so 
theres really not much of an excuse here except maybe production budgets. 
Animation attacks are all the same, but then again, so did many other games 
of the same before. Still, it's made in unity. I dont think an archer 
actually firing arrows or a mage going pew pew with a staff would hurt. 
Likewise, the scratch animation to indicate damage to player occupies all 3 
lanes, making it difficult to actually determine how to dodge an attack 
youve seen. This forces a lot of guesswork which feels kinda cheap 
especially during boss battles who does insane damage every time. Lastly, 
credits are not shared by each hero so you have to grind from scratcheach 
time you unlock one. This one i can look past though since you do want the 
grind to familiarize yourself with their skills.

This game is a simplistic, yet challenging JRPG-like Action game. Although the Mechanics are basically not that complicated they are geniously designed and the large amount of content is great, too.  But there are also some downsides: The UI is pretty unintuitive and the "tutorial" monologues throw lots of information at the player he can't even handle yet at the beginning of the game. Seriously, why do you tell the player how your leveling systems works if he doesn't even have any credits to use it yet? At least they did the counter attack indicator pretty well. Plus, the credits of roll from the downside to the upside. I'm having a touchscreen, I can also scroll through the credits myself!!! Additionally the development team isn't even that great, so... Why does no developer get that credits can also be interactive?! That's a big downside from my point of view.  Sidenote: If your reaction time is much slower than normal this game may not be suited for you

Thanks for making the game free to try ($4 and change before sale) however there's a ton of IAP thats offered before even playing one round of this 'game'. Tap one of 3 directional buttons to dodge an attack and tap sword button to attack opponent, fine ok. It's not for me but "based on skill" as some reviewers mention isnt totally accurate. You upgrade your hero to withstand more damage and deal more damage. And a heal button. There's barely a story line the graphics and music are 8bit, the BGM or "boring game music" gets annoying quickly while vibrations from CPU attacks depletes battery. It's basically Mike Tyson's Punch out for NES except that had more than one colour, a storyline and no ads or IAP for whats supposed to be a paid game based on "skill".
